<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1436,1069,1526]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis box="[199,313,1214,1237]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Often sexually dimorphic, with males varying in body size (
<figureCitation box="[1038,1177,1213,1238]" captionStart="FIGURES 61–65" captionStartId="40.[151,264,1754,1777]" captionTargetBox="[159,1435,195,1730]" captionTargetId="figure-68@40.[151,1436,195,1733]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURES 61–65. Phlaeothrips-lineage. Heads 61–64: (61) Holothrips; (62) Hoplothrips; (63) Hoplandrothrips hylaius, small male; (64) Hoplandrothrips hylaius, large male. (65) Hyidiothrips brunneus, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918152" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918152/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Figs 63, 64</figureCitation>
); head shape variable, usually longer than wide, constricted behind eyes, reticulate dorsally (
<figureCitation box="[982,1072,1249,1274]" captionStart="FIGURES 61–65" captionStartId="40.[151,264,1754,1777]" captionTargetBox="[159,1435,195,1730]" captionTargetId="figure-68@40.[151,1436,195,1733]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURES 61–65. Phlaeothrips-lineage. Heads 61–64: (61) Holothrips; (62) Hoplothrips; (63) Hoplandrothrips hylaius, small male; (64) Hoplandrothrips hylaius, large male. (65) Hyidiothrips brunneus, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918152" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918152/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 64</figureCitation>
); postocular setae usually well developed, wide apart; stylets usually retracted to eyes and close together medially, rarely short and wider apart; mouth cone variable; antennae 8-segmented, III with 3 (or 2–4) sensoria, IV with 4; pronotum usually with 5 pairs of major setae, major males with aa setae unusually long, notopleural sutures complete; basantra absent; mesopresternum transverse, or divided into three plates; sternopleural sutures present; fore tarsal tooth present in both sexes, male fore femur often with pair of apical tubercles; fore wings usually weakly constricted medially, with duplicated cilia; pelta bell-shaped; tergites II–VII each with 2 pairs of wing-retaining setae; tube shorter than head, anal setae usually as long as tube or longer; male sternite VIII with or without pore plate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
